member.name: T:Amazon.PowerShell.Cmdlets.IOTST.GetIOTSTTunnelListCmdlet
member.summary:
List all tunnels for an AWS account. Tunnels are listed by creation time in descending order, newer tunnels will be listed before older tunnels.
This cmdlet automatically pages all available results to the pipeline - parameters related to iteration are only needed if you want to manually control the paginated output. To disable autopagination, use -NoAutoIteration.

para.para: The name of the IoT thing associated with the destination device.
The maximum number of results to return at once.
A token to retrieve the next set of results.

summary.para:
Note: This parameter is only used if you are manually controlling output pagination of the service API call.
In order to manually control output pagination, use '-NextToken $null' for the first call and '-NextToken $AWSHistory.LastServiceResponse.NextToken' for subsequent calls.

member.name: P:Amazon.PowerShell.Cmdlets.IOTST.GetIOTSTTunnelListCmdlet.NoAutoIteration
member.summary: By default the cmdlet will auto-iterate and retrieve all results to the pipeline by performing multiple service calls. If set, the cmdlet will retrieve only the next 'page' of results using the value of NextToken as the start point.

member.name: T:Amazon.PowerShell.Cmdlets.IOTST.OpenIOTSTTunnelCmdlet
member.summary: Creates a new tunnel, and returns two client access tokens for clients to use to connect to the AWS IoT Secure Tunneling proxy server. .

para.para: A short text description of the tunnel.
The maximum amount of time (in minutes) a tunnel can remain open. If not specified, maxLifetimeTimeoutMinutes defaults to 720 minutes. Valid values are from 1 minute to 12 hours (720 minutes)

A list of service names that identity the target application. Currently, you can only specify a single name. The AWS IoT client running on the destination device reads this value and uses it to look up a port or an IP address and a port. The AWS IoT client instantiates the local proxy which uses this information to connect to the destination application.
The name of the IoT thing to which you want to connect.
